The article discusses the new commitments made by the White House to support computer science education in K-12 schools. These commitments include more than 60 school districts offering computer science courses, over $20 million in philanthropic contributions to train teachers, new partnerships with the National Science Foundation, efforts to increase the participation of women and underrepresented minorities in computer science, and collaborations with organizations such as Teach for America and the National Math and Science Initiative. The article also highlights the importance of computer science education in the future job market and the need to broaden diversity in the field.